<h2 id="best-practices">Best practices</h2>
<p><strong>Use concise, accurate, and specific labels.</strong> Avoid vague and abstract language like &quot;Get started&quot; or &quot;Learn more&quot;. Prefer explicit labels instead, like &quot;Find doctor&quot; or &quot;Schedule appointment&quot;. Accurate and specific language improves user confidence and engagement (<a href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/information-scent/#:~:text=Perhaps%20the%20most,to%20click%20it." title="Information Scent: How Users Decide Where to Go Next - Nielsen Norman Group">1</a>), while overly broad calls to action can mislead, confuse, and fail to interest users (<a href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/get-started/" title="Get Started Stops Users - Nielsen Norman Group">2</a>).</p>
<p><strong>Use sentence case.</strong> All-uppercase text is slower and more difficult to read for all users (<a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/low-vision-needs/#capitalization">3</a>) but particularly for those with dyslexia (<a href="https://www.bdadyslexia.org.uk/advice/employers/creating-a-dyslexia-friendly-workplace/dyslexia-friendly-style-guide#:~:text=Avoid%20text%20in%20uppercase/capital%20letters%20and%20small%20caps%2C%20which%20can%20be%20less%20familiar%20to%20the%20reader%20and%20harder%20to%20read.">4</a>). Furthermore, screen readers sometimes interpret certain uppercased words as common initialisms (such as ADD or US), and may erroneously spell out those words letter by letter (<a href="https://webaim.org/techniques/screenreader/#:~:text=Screen%20readers%20try%20to%20pronounce%20acronyms%2C%20if%20there%20are%20sufficient%20vowels/consonants%20to%20be%20pronounceable.%20Otherwise%2C%20they%20spell%20out%20the%20letters.">5</a>).</p>
<h2 id="usage">Usage</h2>
<h3 id="links">Links</h3>
<p>A button can point to a link using the <a href="#link-attribute"><code>link</code> attribute</a>.</p>
<p>Optionally, the link can be opened in a new tab with the <a href="#new-tab-attribute"><code>new-tab</code> attribute</a>.</p>

{% embed "@tch/includes/example.twig" %}
{% block content %}
<tcds-button link="https://www.texaschildrens.org/" new-tab>Go to texaschildrens.org</tcds-button>
{% endblock %}
{% endembed %}


<h3 id="icons">Icons</h3>
<p><a href="/components/icon#library">Icons</a> can be added to a button with the <a href="#icon-attribute"><code>icon</code> attribute</a>.</p>

{% embed "@tch/includes/example.twig" %}
{% block content %}
<tcds-button icon="info">Icon button</tcds-button>
{% endblock %}
{% endembed %}


<p>Icons can be right-aligned by including the word <code>right</code> in the <code>icon</code> attribute.</p>

{% embed "@tch/includes/example.twig" %}
{% block content %}
<tcds-button icon="right chevron-right">Right icon</tcds-button>
{% endblock %}
{% endembed %}


<p>Button labels can be hidden when using an icon by including the word <code>only</code> in the <code>icon</code> attribute. However, a text label must still be provided for assistive technology (see <a href="#icon-only-buttons">&sect; Icon-only buttons</a>).</p>

{% embed "@tch/includes/example.twig" %}
{% block content %}
<tcds-button icon="only x">Close</tcds-button>
{% endblock %}
{% endembed %}


<h3 id="variants">Variants</h3>
<p>Secondary, ghost, and UI buttons can be created with the <a href="#variant-attribute"><code>variant</code> attribute</a>.</p>

{% embed "@tch/includes/example.twig" %}
{% block content %}
<div class="row gap-loose">
  <tcds-button variant="secondary">Secondary button</tcds-button>
  <tcds-button variant="ghost" icon="right chevron-right">Ghost button</tcds-button>
  <tcds-button variant="ui" icon="only x">UI button</tcds-button>
</div>
{% endblock %}
{% block code %}
<tcds-button variant="secondary">Secondary button</tcds-button>
<tcds-button variant="ghost" icon="right chevron-right">Ghost button</tcds-button>
<tcds-button variant="ui" icon="only x">UI button</tcds-button>
{% endblock %}
{% endembed %}


<h3 id="sizes">Sizes</h3>
<p>Small and large buttons can be created with the <a href="#size-attribute"><code>size</code> attribute</a>.</p>

{% embed "@tch/includes/example.twig" %}
{% block content %}
<div class="column gap-normal">
  <tcds-button size="small">Small button</tcds-button>
  <tcds-button>Default button</tcds-button>
  <tcds-button size="large">Large button</tcds-button>
</div>
{% endblock %}
{% block code %}
<tcds-button size="small">Small button</tcds-button>
<tcds-button>Default button</tcds-button>
<tcds-button size="large">Large button</tcds-button>
{% endblock %}
{% endembed %}


<p>Full width buttons can be created, optionally in combination with any <code>size</code>:</p>

{% embed "@tch/includes/example.twig" %}
{% block content %}
<tcds-button size="large full-width">Large full-width button</tcds-button>
{% endblock %}
{% endembed %}


<h3 id="form-types">Form types</h3>
<p>The <a href="#type-attribute"><code>type</code> attribute</a> allows you to set a valid <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/2011/WD-html5-20110525/the-button-element.html#attr-button-type"><code>type</code> HTML attribute</a> on the Button. For example, a submit button for a form:</p>

{% embed "@tch/includes/example.twig" %}
{% block content %}
<tcds-button type="submit">Submit form</tcds-button>
{% endblock %}
{% endembed %}


<h2 id="accessibility">Accessibility</h2>
<h3 id="touch-target-size">Touch target size</h3>
<p>Research shows touch targets should be a minimum of 1cm &times; 1cm (<a href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/touch-target-size/" title="Touch Targets on Touch Screens - Nielsen Norman Group">1</a>), which is enforced by this component&#39;s stylesheet. Having a sufficient touch target size increases general usability for all users, but most notably accomodates users with motor function and vision impairments.</p>
<h3 id="icon-only-buttons">Icon-only buttons</h3>
<p>Always provide a text label for buttons, even if you only want an icon to display. The <code>only</code> value of the <code>icon</code> attribute will visually hide the label, using it instead as the <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG20-TECHS/ARIA14.html"><code>aria-label</code> attribute</a> for screen readers, and the <code>title</code> tooltip for mouse users.</p>
<p>While icon-only buttons are possible, try to always keep the text label visible; what an icon is supposed to represent may not be universally clear or efficiently understood.</p>
